title: Walt Whitman to William Sloane Kennedy, 20 June [1886]
text: June 20—Evn'gDear W S KI send you a note of introduction to J A Symonds—whom I think most likely & valuable, for the purpose you spoke of—(if I rightly understood it)—Symonds has leisure, has long been a reader of L of G.—& I have heard has for some time been wanting to have something to say in print about it—If possible send him at first a copy of your complete book, in proof from the types, or type-written in slips, complete—In fact get two or three such copies, & send me one in advance—No doubt I would see many important corrections to be made—or additions—or elisions—Maybe (though may-be not too)—J A S would like the chance of giving his say, in such introduction—I dont think well of requesting any thing from Dowden—W WYour Ruskin book has been rec'd & I have been reading it all day— Walt Whitman to William Sloane Kennedy, 20 June [1886]
